entry.title: Avoid dangling pointer in StyledLabel.
entry.content:
During layout and between calling AddCustomView and the next layout

run a StyleRange's RangeStyleInfo may have a raw pointer to a view

stored inside StyledLabel's custom_views_ member.

If StyledLabel is destroyed prior the next layout call, then

custom_views_ should outlive style_ranges_, or else the raw pointers

inside the StyleRanges can become dangling.



This CL switches the definition order of the custom_views_ and

style_ranges_ members to make sure that this is the case.

entry.title: android: Allow Paint Preview to happen with native
entry.content:
The decision whether to display the Paint Preview depends on the

heuristic detecting cold start: the start is considered _not_ cold (i.e.

warm) when the native library has already been loaded and initialized.



We hypothesize that recently the library started becoming initialized

very early in the process lifetime. One of the causes for it is

asynchronous library loading on a separate thread.



As a result of recent changes, the volume of UMA samples for

"Browser.PaintPreview.TabbedPlayer.TimeToFirstBitmap" has dropped

dramatically, leading to Paint Preview becoming less useful.



This change attempts to use another heuristic for a cold start:

1. the app process creation is caused by an activity

2. no activity is paused prior to pre-inflation of the tabbed activity



The (1) uses a new "process creation reason" trick available on P+

devices and falls back to time-based detection for older devices.

entry.content:
This reverts commit d397fe50489c3e5b4c582352b61995d3a3a80f32.



Reason for revert: We confirmed that the initial patch did trigger the failure. However it itself was not the direct cause. crbug.com/1488444 goes into test ordering and side effects of the WEBGL_video_texture leading to differing behaviours.

entry.title: Deduplicate batched cookie access details
entry.content:
With this CL, we use a std::set to ensure that we avoid sending

IPCs with redundant cookie access details. Some clients care about

counts, so we include a count along with the deduplicated details.



The order of the elements are determined by the position that the

last duplicate would have occupied in the non-deduplicated list.

Eg, consider the following:



ABACCABACDA

^ ^^^

The caret is below the last instance of each duplicated entry. We

take the elements with the carets and return them in this order:

BCDA.



I also noticed that the cookie list was not used in OnCookiesRead

so I've removed that plumbing in this patch as well.



credit: dtapuska@ for suggesting that we avoid storing redundant

data, suggesting a dictionary-like data with counts, and checking

for compression percentage. jbroman@ for suggesting std::tie/

make_tuple for combining r and l values for comparison.

entry.title: [text-spacing-trim] Avoid redundant entries in features
entry.content:
This patch fixes two redundant operations:

1. `ShapeSegment` can run multiple times for the same range

when there are font cascading or fallback. `HanKerning`

adds features each time, causing redundant entries.

This patch fixes this by resetting the `FontFeatures`,

similar to what `CapsFeatureSettingsScopedOverlay` does.

2. `ShapeSegment` gives the whole range given to `Shape`, not

the range of the segment it is currently shaping. This lets

`HanKerning` to scan the same text multiple times.



These redundancy is not observable, as HarfBuzz ignores

redundant font features, other than the unnecessarily wasted

time and memory.



The `FontFeature` argument is changed from a reference to a

pointer because `HanKerning` will keep the pointer until it

is destructed.



This patch has no behavior changes.

entry.title: Renderer rewrite: Annotate dangling pointers
entry.content:
This patch should effectively be a no-op, replacing one flag

`ExperimentalRenderer` by another `DanglingUntriaged`. Both

currently share the same value, but a different meaning.



Kalvin applied the MiraclePtr rewrite in the renderer process:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4904523

We still need to opt-in checking them with the DanglingPointerDetector.



This applies pass 1 of the DanglingPointerDetector annotation process:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1GmGagDZtxHpWXJDKqlmzSaqaO5D-pavfH5IRGITfANs/edit#heading=h.s23pazuno76f



1. Rebase and apply the instrumentation CL

2. Compile the compiler: ./tools/clang/scripts/build.py --without-fuchsia

3. Run all the gtests. You can use this script.

4. Concatenate all the output_*, `filter`, `sort -nr`, `uniq`.

5. Install and run https://github.com/ArthurSonzogni/chrome-dangling-ptr-apply-edit

6. Run git cl format

7. Run git checkout origin/main -- base/allocator/partition_allocator/pointers/raw_ptr_unittest.cc

The off-the-record ChromeBrowserState is destroyed when the user closes

the observation in an overloaded -setBrowser:. This ensure the pointer

entry.title: Reland "PRESUBMIT: Warn against adding new dangling pointers."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 8228ad6aeff42442cd08345725249e10f4abdf77



What happens in the reland:

---------------------------



I added an early return when `input_api.nodiff` is true. This disable

the check completely.



Performance evaluation:

-----------------------



Because the original presubmit check was reverted due to the performance

cost when running `git cl presubmit --all`, it comes the question of the

performance cost during normal `git cl presubmit`.



I am evaluating the cost to be in the range: [-0.178%, -1.04%].

This is the 95 confidence interval using a t-test.



This was tested on a very large patch modifying 535 files. The data was:



Without With

------- ----

91.1s 91.5s

91.6s 91.8s

91.6s 92.1s

90.9s 92.0s

91.3s 91.9s



Original change's description:

> PRESUBMIT: Warn against adding new dangling pointers.

>

> The DanglingPointerDetector is enabled on the CQ. It means we are now

> blocking new dangling pointers and can detect regressions.

>

> This blocks ~10 patches per day. The error message contains links toward

> the documentation and a guide to fix dangling pointers:

> - docs/dangling_ptr.md

> - docs/dangling_ptr_guide.md

>

> This is enough for most developers to fix them. However, it happens some

> are simply adding new `DanglingUntriaged` occurrences. Most are

> copy-pasting nearby code thinking this is the correct way to do.

>

> This patch adds a PRESUBMIT warning developers.
